def get_dates(data):
    dates = data.loc[:, [i not in ["countyFIPS","County Name", "State", "StateFIPS"] for i in data]] #Extract non dates
    
    dates.columns = pd.to_datetime(dates.columns) #Fix columns to be date times
    
    dates = dates.loc[:, [(i <= datetime.datetime(2020, 12, 27)) and (i >= datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 6)) for i in dates]] #Extract correct time
    return dates
death_dates = get_dates(deaths)

def get_weekly_stats(dates): #Note: was written for deaths, but should work the same for infect

    weeks = [range(i, i + 7) for i in range(0, len(dates.columns), 7)]
    dates.iloc[:, weeks[0]]
    
    stats = pd.DataFrame({"week": [],"mean" : [], "median" : [], "mode" : []})
    
    for i in range(len(weeks)):
        date = dates.iloc[:, weeks[i]].iloc[0, :].keys()[0]
        #print(date)
        week = dates.iloc[:, weeks[i]].sum(axis = 1)
        #print(week)
        #print(week.mean())
        #print(week.median())
        #print(week.mode())
        #print(death_stats)
        new_row = pd.DataFrame({"week": date,"mean" : week.mean(), "median" : week.median(), "mode" : week.mode()})
        stats = pd.concat([stats, new_row])
    return stats
death_stats = get_weekly_stats(death_dates)

def get_state_dates(data, state : str):
    '''Filter out all data not from a given state from data'''
    data = data[data["State"] == state]
    dates = data.loc[:, [i not in ["countyFIPS","County Name", "State", "StateFIPS"] for i in data]] #Extract non dates
    
    dates.columns = pd.to_datetime(dates.columns) #Fix columns to be date times
    
    dates = dates.loc[:, [(i <= datetime.datetime(2020, 12, 27)) and (i >= datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 6)) for i in dates]] #Extract correct time
    return dates
nc_deaths = get_state_dates(deaths, "NC")

def get_normalized_data(data, population):
    '''Takes a series as input, adds 1 to all values in the series, divides by (population/100000), and preforms np.log10 on all cells'''
    
    data += 1
    
    data /= (population / 100000)
    
    data = data.agg(np.log10)
    
    return data
get_normalized_data(nc_deaths.sum(), nc_pop)

MI Seems to have high realative deaths, but low relative cases.¶

For cases, all of them aside from ND follow the normal curve. ND seems to have linear growth whereas the others kind of look like sigmoid functions (They are not, but I don't remember the proper term for this kind of distrabution.)¶

For deaths, MI seems to be near constant until the start of december, when it starts to grow¶

The peaks are at the end of the graph. This is because during this time the infection was worsening with time.¶

The situation regarding North Decota can be explained by the losening of quarantine restrictions starting in October 1st in that state (Source: https://www.thedickinsonpress.com/newsmd/health-experts-thrash-north-dakotas-new-quarantine-guidelines-this-is-highly-dangerous)¶
